{{Infobox mountain range | name=Tangra Mountains | photo=Tangra.jpg | photo_caption=Central Tangra Mountains | country=Antarctica | country_type=Continent | region_type =Region | region=South Shetland Islands | parent= | border= | coordinates = | length_km=30 | length_note = | width_km=8 | width_note = | highest=Mount Friesland | elevation_m=1700 | elevation_note=<ref name=AAJ2004/> | range_coordinates = {{coord|62|40|00|S|60|06|00|W|type:mountain|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | range_coordinates_note = | geology= | period=| orogeny= | map_image=Tangra-Mountains-location-map.png | map_caption=Location of Tangra Mountains on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands }} [[File:Livingston-Island-Map-2010-15.png|thumb|Topographic map of Livingston Island.]] [[File:Tangra-Great-Needle.jpg|thumb|right|[[Helmet Peak, Livingston Island|Helmet Peak]] and [[Great Needle Peak]] from [[Kuzman Knoll]].]] [[File:Presian.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mount Friesland]] from the west slope of [[Lyaskovets Peak]].]] [[File:Great-Needle.jpg|thumb|right|[[Great Needle Peak]] from [[Bransfield Strait]].]] [[File:Bruix.jpg|thumb|right|[[Delchev Ridge]] from [[Melnik Peak]].]] '''Tangra Mountains''' (in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] ''Тангра планина'', 'Tangra planina' \'tan-gra pla-ni-'na\) ({{coord|62|40|00|S|60|06|00|W|}}) form the principal mountain range of [[Livingston Island]] in the [[South Shetland Islands]], [[Antarctica]]. The range had been nameless until 2001, when it was named after the [[Bulgars|Bulgar]] god [[Tengri|Tangra]].<ref>[http://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/search_names_action.cfm Tangra Mountains.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220034212/http://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/search_names_action.cfm |date=20 December 2010 }} SCAR Composite Antarctic Gazetteer.</ref>
Tangra Mountains are 30&nbsp;km long between [[Barnard Point]] and [[Renier Point]], 8&nbsp;km wide, and are bounded by [[Moon Bay]] and [[Huron Glacier]] to the north, [[Huntress Glacier]] to the northwest, [[False Bay, Livingston Island|False Bay]] to the west, and [[Bransfield Strait]] to the southeast, and is linked to [[Bowles Ridge]] by [[Wörner Gap]], and to [[Pliska Ridge]] by [[Nesebar Gap]]. The mountain is divided in three principal ridges: [[Friesland Ridge]] in the west, [[Levski Ridge]] in the centre, and [[Delchev Ridge]] in the east.
The peaks and slopes of Tangra are heavily glaciated, and drained by the glaciers Huron, Huntress, [[Ruen Icefall]], [[Peshtera Glacier|Peshtera]], [[Charity Glacier|Charity]], [[Tarnovo Ice Piedmont]], [[Prespa Glacier|Prespa]], [[Macy Glacier|Macy]], [[Boyana Glacier|Boyana]], [[Srebarna Glacier|Srebarna]], [[Magura Glacier|Magura]], [[Dobrudzha Glacier|Dobrudzha]], [[Ropotamo Glacier|Ropotamo]], [[Strandzha Glacier|Strandzha]], [[Pautalia Glacier|Pautalia]], [[Sopot Ice Piedmont]], and [[Iskar Glacier|Iskar]].
[[Camp Academia]] in the northwestern foothills of [[Zograf Peak]] is the perfect gateway to central Tangra Mountains via [[Catalunyan Saddle]] (1260&nbsp;m) to the south and [[Lozen Saddle]] (437&nbsp;m) to the east. Catalunyan Saddle was occupied by a bivouac of the [[Tangra 2004/05|Tangra 2004/05 Exploration]] team on 14–16 December 2004.
== Friesland Ridge == {{Main|Friesland Ridge}} [[Friesland Ridge]] is 15.5&nbsp;km long from [[Botev Point]] in the southwest to [[Shipka Saddle]] to the northeast. The summit [[Mount Friesland]] ({{coord|62|40|14.9|S|60|11|10.7|W|}}) rises to exactly 1700&nbsp;m. It was accurately measured by GPS in December 2003 by the Omega Foundation expedition led by [[Damien Gildea]], which made the second ascent of Mount Friesland.<ref name=AAJ2004/> Other main peaks are [[St. Boris Peak|St. Boris]] (1699&nbsp;m),<ref name="Boyanov">D. Boyanov and N. Petkov. The peaks of Tangra Mountains: Project report Part Two 2016/17. Sofia, February 2017. 8 pp. (in Bulgarian)</ref> [[Simeon Peak|Simeon]] (1580&nbsp;m), [[St. Cyril Peak|St. Cyril]] (1505&nbsp;m), [[Lyaskovets Peak|Lyaskovets]] (1473&nbsp;m), [[Presian Ridge]] (1456&nbsp;m), [[St. Methodius Peak|St. Methodius]] (1180&nbsp;m), [[Academia Peak|Academia]] (1253&nbsp;m), and [[Zograf Peak|Zograf]] (1011&nbsp;m). First ascents: Mount Friesland by [[Francesc Sàbat]] and [[Jorge Enrique]] from [[Juan Carlos I Base|Juan Carlos&nbsp;I Base]] on 30 December 1991; [[Lyaskovets Peak]] by [[Lyubomir Ivanov (explorer)|L.&nbsp;Ivanov]] and [[Doychin Vasilev|D.&nbsp;Vasilev]] from [[Camp Academia]] on 14 December 2004; [[Zograf Peak]] by L.&nbsp;Ivanov from Camp Academia on 31 December 2004; and [[St. Boris Peak|St.&nbsp;Boris Peak]] by D.&nbsp;Boyanov and N.&nbsp;Petkov from Camp Academia area on 23 January 2016.<ref name="Boyanov"/>
== Levski Ridge == {{Main|Levski Ridge}} [[Levski Ridge]] is 8&nbsp;km long between [[Shipka Saddle]] to the west and [[Devin Saddle]] to the east, and 8&nbsp;km wide between [[Cherepish Ridge]] to the north and [[Christoff Cliff]] to the south. The summit [[Great Needle Peak]] ({{coord|62|40|15|S|60|03|10|W|}}) rises to 1680&nbsp;m, and was first ascended and GPS-surveyed by the Bulgarian mountaineers Doychin Boyanov, Nikolay Petkov and Aleksander Shopov on 8 January 2015.<ref>N. Petkov and D. Boyanov. [https://web.archive.org/web/20160212175742/http://www.verticalworldbg.com/index.php/worldsummits/21-antarctica-2015 Report of the project ''The Peaks of Tangra Mountains.''] Sofia, 2015. 17 pp. (in Bulgarian)</ref> Other main peaks are [[Levski Peak (Antarctica)|Levski]] (1430&nbsp;m), [[St. Ivan Rilski Col]] (1350&nbsp;m), [[Helmet Peak (Antarctica)|Helmet]] (1254&nbsp;m), [[Serdica Peak|Serdica]] (1200&nbsp;m), [[Vihren Peak|Vihren]] (1150&nbsp;m), [[Ongal Peak|Ongal]] (1149&nbsp;m), and [[Plovdiv Peak|Plovdiv]] (1040&nbsp;m). Other first ascents: [[Ongal Peak]] and [[Komini Peak]] (774&nbsp;m) by [[Lyubomir Ivanov (explorer)|L.&nbsp;Ivanov]] from [[Camp Academia]] on 21 December 2004, and [[Plana Peak]] by D.&nbsp;Boyanov, N.&nbsp;Petkov and A.&nbsp;Shopov on 8 January 2015.
== Delchev Ridge == {{Main|Delchev Ridge}} [[Delchev Ridge]] is 10&nbsp;km long between [[Devin Saddle]] to the west and [[Renier Point]] to the east. The summit [[Delchev Peak]] ({{coord|62|38|28|S|59|56|16|W|}}) rises to 940&nbsp;m, other main peaks are [[Ruse Peak|Ruse]] (800&nbsp;m), [[Asen Peak|Asen]] (800&nbsp;m), [[Peter Peak|Peter]] (800&nbsp;m), [[Kuber Peak|Kuber]] (770&nbsp;m), [[Elena Peak|Elena]] (700&nbsp;m), [[Spartacus Peak|Spartacus]] (650&nbsp;m), [[Yavorov Peak|Yavorov]] (640&nbsp;m), and [[Paisiy Peak|Paisiy]] (550&nbsp;m).
== Mapping == [[United Kingdom|British]] mapping of the mountains in 1968, [[Spain|Spanish]] mapping in 1991, Omega Foundation mapping in 2004, [[Bulgaria]]n mapping in 2005 and 2009 from [[topography|topographic surveys]] in 1995/96 and [[Tangra 2004/05|2004/05]]. * S. Soccol, D. Gildea and J. Bath. [http://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/mapcat/display_map.cfm?map_id=13271 Livingston Island, Antarctica.] Scale 1:100000 satellite map. The Omega Foundation, USA, 2004. * L.L. Ivanov et al. [[:Image:Livingston-Greenwich-map.jpg|Antarctica: Livingston Island and Greenwich Island, South Shetland Islands]] (from English Strait to Morton Strait, with illustrations and ice-cover distribution). Scale 1:100000 topographic map. Sofia: Antarctic Place-names Commission of Bulgaria, 2005. * L.L. Ivanov. [[:commons:File:Livingston-Island-Map-2010.jpg|Antarctica: Livingston Island and Greenwich, Robert, Snow and Smith Islands.]] Scale 1:120000 topographic map. Troyan: Manfred Wörner Foundation, 2010. {{ISBN|978-954-92032-9-5}} (First edition 2009. {{ISBN|978-954-92032-6-4}}) * L.L. Ivanov. [[:commons:File:Livingston-Island-Map-2010-15.png|Antarctica: Livingston Island and Smith Island]]. Scale 1:100000 topographic map. Manfred Wörner Foundation, 2017. {{ISBN|978-619-90008-3-0}}
